docs.abstract: Online orders have surged for retailers in the pandemic, as curbside pickup helps Americans satisfy their desire to hop in a car and drive to the store.
docs.snippet: Online orders have surged for retailers in the pandemic, as curbside pickup helps Americans satisfy their desire to hop in a car and drive to the store.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the pandemic forced Dick’s Sporting Goods to close its hundreds of stores in March, the retailer hustled to set up curbside pickup within two days. Its initial attempt, though, was just this side of a children’s lemonade stand.

headline.main: Customers Still Like to Shop in Person, Even if They Get Only to the Curb
headline.print_headline: Shoppers Stream to Curbside, Transforming Economics of Retail

byline.original: By Sapna Maheshwari and Michael Corkery

docs.abstract: Spurred by recent social unrest, many U.S. companies are trying to make it easier for workers, and urging their customers, to cast their ballots.
docs.snippet: Spurred by recent social unrest, many U.S. companies are trying to make it easier for workers, and urging their customers, to cast their ballots.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bank of America is offering employees up to three hours of paid time to vote this year. The spirits company Diageo North America has declared a no-meeting day on Nov. 3. Best Buy is closing stores until noon that day, and PayPal is offering a half day, paid, to workers who volunteer at polling places.

headline.main: Paid Time Off, Free Fries: How Corporate America Is Getting Out the Vote
headline.print_headline: How Corporate America Is Helping to Get Out the Vote

byline.original: By Kate Kelly and Sapna Maheshwari

docs.abstract: There is heartbreak almost everywhere you look, our columnist says, but the stock market usually rises anyway.
docs.snippet: There is heartbreak almost everywhere you look, our columnist says, but the stock market usually rises anyway.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a year of serial crises, solace for many people has come from an unlikely source: the stock market.

headline.main: For Long-Term Investors, Small Things Like Presidential Elections Don’t Matter
headline.print_headline: For Long-Term Investors, Elections Are No Sweat

docs.abstract: In this Oscar-nominated documentary, an indomitable matriarch strives to keep her family together while fighting for the release of her incarcerated husband.
docs.snippet: In this Oscar-nominated documentary, an indomitable matriarch strives to keep her family together while fighting for the release of her incarcerated husband.
docs.lead_paragraph: Fox Rich is a fighter. The entrepreneur, author, and mother of six boys has spent the last two decades campaigning for the release of her husband, Rob G. Rich, who is serving a 60-year sentence at Louisiana State Penitentiary for a bank robbery they both committed in 1997.

headline.main: Introducing ‘Time,’ a Film From The Times and Amazon Studios

docs.abstract: The picturesque Gard desperately needs more employment. But environmentalists are pushing back at what they see as a looming blight.
docs.snippet: The picturesque Gard desperately needs more employment. But environmentalists are pushing back at what they see as a looming blight.
docs.lead_paragraph: FOURNÈS, France — On a sultry September morning, Claudie Cortellini headed into the vineyards to survey the grapes that go into her family’s heady Côtes du Rhône wines. In recent years, she has fought to ensure a good harvest as the climate grows warmer. But these days, she is facing an even bigger foe: a giant Amazon sorting center slated for construction near her land.

headline.main: Are Amazon Jobs Worth 1,400 Loads of Traffic? French Region Is Split
headline.print_headline: Boon or Bane? France Divided Over Amazon

docs.abstract: Lawmakers said they found multiple problems with each of the four giant tech companies.
docs.snippet: Lawmakers said they found multiple problems with each of the four giant tech companies.
docs.lead_paragraph: House lawmakers released a scathing report on four of the world’s largest tech companies, accusing them of abusing their market power. The report, which was released on Tuesday and concludes a 16-month investigation into Amazon, Apple, Facebook and Google, recommended breaking up the companies and passing the most sweeping reforms to antitrust laws in decades.

headline.main: 12 Accusations in the Damning House Report on Amazon, Apple, Facebook and Google

byline.original: By Mike Isaac, Steve Lohr, Jack Nicas and Daisuke Wakabayashi

docs.abstract: How antitrust lawyer Lina Khan is taking on the most powerful men in Silicon Valley.
docs.snippet: How antitrust lawyer Lina Khan is taking on the most powerful men in Silicon Valley.
docs.lead_paragraph: It finally looks as if Big Tech may face some breakups. Lawmakers are interrogating tech C.E.O.s on Capitol Hill while the Justice Department pursues a landmark antitrust case against Google. For decades, tech giants have avoided such scrutiny — hiding behind the idea that their products are free, beneficial, even beloved.

docs.abstract: A House report on how to limit the reach of Apple, Amazon, Google and Facebook has been delayed as Democrats and Republicans split on remedies.
docs.snippet: A House report on how to limit the reach of Apple, Amazon, Google and Facebook has been delayed as Democrats and Republicans split on remedies.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For all the divisions in Washington, one issue that had united Republicans and Democrats in recent years was their animus toward the power of the biggest tech companies.

headline.main: Big Tech Was Their Enemy, Until Partisanship Fractured the Battle Plans

byline.original: By Cecilia Kang and David McCabe

docs.abstract: The move is an escalation of the  pressure being put on executives at the country’s second-largest private employer.
docs.snippet: The move is an escalation of the  pressure being put on executives at the country’s second-largest private employer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Workers at Amazon are calling on groups around the country to help shut down Amazon warehouses temporarily on Halloween if the company does not give all its employees a paid day off to vote.

headline.main: Amazon workers threaten to shut down warehouses if employees don’t get a day off to vote.

docs.abstract: A damning congressional report about Big Tech helps make the case to break up Jeff Bezos’ empire.
docs.snippet: A damning congressional report about Big Tech helps make the case to break up Jeff Bezos’ empire.
docs.lead_paragraph: We tend to credit Amazon’s enormous reach to its inventiveness. Jeff Bezos has built a logistics operation that rivals UPS and FedEx in the volume of packages it delivers to consumers in the United States. Amazon’s Alexa is the dominant operating system in the new arena of voice-enabled devices and web access.

headline.main: Don’t Let Amazon Get Any Bigger
headline.print_headline: Don’t Let Amazon Get Any Bigger
